---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { SITE_URL } from "../../lib/siteMeta";

export function getStaticPaths() {
  return [{ params: { locale: "en" } }];
}

const title = "Methodology - Utildesk";
const description =
  "How Utildesk curates AI tools, guides and recommendations: sources, selection, affiliate transparency and editorial review.";
const pageUrl = `${SITE_URL}/en/methodology/`;

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "WebPage",
  name: title,
  description,
  url: pageUrl,
  inLanguage: "en",
  dateModified: "2026-07-17",
  isPartOf: {
    "@type": "WebSite",
    name: "Utildesk",
    url: SITE_URL,
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout locale="en" title={title} description={description}>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <link rel="canonical" href={pageUrl} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <article class="tool-akte sheet-wrap legal-sheet methodology-sheet">
    <nav class="akte-crumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/en/">Back to directory</a>
      <span class="akte-crumb-sep">/</span>
      <span class="akte-crumb-current">Methodology</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="sheet-head">
      <div class="sheet-head-kicker">editorial policy / review rules</div>
      <h1 class="sheet-head-h1">Methodology<span class="akte-mast-dot">.</span></h1>
      <p class="sheet-head-dek">
        Utildesk is an independent directory for AI tools and productive workflows.
        We organize tools so readers can quickly understand what a product is useful for,
        which alternatives exist and when a deeper look is worthwhile.
      </p>
      <div class="sheet-head-meta">
        <span><strong>No</strong> paid rankings</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Public sources, editorial review</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Updated: 17 July 2026</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="akte-article legal-article">
      <div class="akte-article-body legal-prose">
        <div>
          <h2>How tools are added</h2>
          <p>
            New entries are based on public sources such as provider websites, documentation, pricing pages,
            product launches and editorial research. Before a tool becomes visible, we check its name,
            category, pricing signal, tags, provider link and obvious duplicates.
          </p>

          <h2>Which sources take priority</h2>
          <p>
            We verify product capabilities, prices, privacy and technical limits first in official product
            pages, documentation, changelogs, security material and privacy policies. Independent specialist
            sources add a second perspective where practical experience, market comparison or controversy
            matters. Claims that can change quickly are checked again against the primary source instead of
            being copied from an old summary.
          </p>

          <h2>What “editorially reviewed” means</h2>
          <p>
            A tool file receives this label only after a manual German and English editorial pass. We check use
            cases, limitations, cost model, privacy questions, alternatives, internal links and consistency with
            the cited sources. Automatically prepared entries keep their disclosure until that review is complete.
          </p>

          <h2>How guides are created</h2>
          <p>
            Guides are built from multiple sources and comparison points. They should provide context,
            link to concrete tools and avoid pure promotional copy. Candidates are reviewed in the final
            page design before publication. When an AI system assists with research, briefing or a draft, final
            source selection, interpretation and approval remain with the Utildesk editorial team. AI output is
            never treated as a source by itself.
          </p>

          <h2>Affiliate transparency</h2>
          <p>
            When a tool has a referral link, Utildesk may receive a commission after signup. These links do
            not replace editorial judgment: paid slots, bought rankings and sponsored lists are not part of
            the concept.
          </p>

          <h2>Index quality</h2>
          <p>
            Not every generated detail page needs to enter search immediately. Priority goes to curated tools,
            strong guides, categories and pages with standalone value. Duplicates, very thin entries and pure
            long-tail variants are reduced or excluded from indexing.
          </p>

          <h2>Updates and corrections</h2>
          <p>
            Prices, capabilities and product names change. We correct factual errors and broken links after
            verification, and update the visible review or publication date after a substantial revision. Reports
            are prioritized by relevance and checked against the authoritative source. A correction never buys a
            provider a more favorable verdict.
          </p>

          <h2>Report an issue</h2>
          <p>
            If an entry is outdated, miscategorized or unclear, use the contact address in the
            <a href="/en/imprint/">imprint</a>. Notes about wrong prices, broken links and missing alternatives
            directly improve the next editorial pass. Please do not include personal or confidential data.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="sheet-foot">
      <div>
        <div class="sheet-foot-kicker">Practical consequence</div>
        <p class="sheet-foot-line">Utildesk evaluates usefulness and context, not market noise.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sheet-foot-actions">
        <a class="akte-action akte-action-primary" href="/en/tools/">Tool index</a>
        <a class="akte-action akte-action-ghost" href="/en/ratgeber/">Guides</a>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
